# Agatha Eliot Mashup — Prompt Template
# ℏKask v0.27.0 - A Minimal Viable Container for Agents
# License: CC-BY-4.0 (attribution required)
# Attribution: "Agatha Eliot Mashup v1.0, The Curator (hKask)"
#
# Style mashup: Agatha Christie (1890-1976) × George Eliot (1819-1880)
#
# A Mixture of Experts replicator: Christie contributes structural architecture
# (closed-circle suspects, clue distribution, the revelation scene); Eliot
# contributes psychological and moral depth (free indirect discourse, the
# inner life, the web of interdependent consciousness). They do not "blend"
# sentence by sentence — they operate at different narrative layers.
#
# =============================================================================
# BLEND MECHANICS
# =============================================================================
#
# Christie contributes:
#   - Closed-circle suspect dynamics: every motive examined in turn
#   - Clue placement as epistemological discipline
#   - The revelation scene: order and method produce pattern from facts
#   - Declarative forensic clarity: "The facts, Madame, the facts."
#   - Structural certainty: the truth can be known
#
# Eliot contributes:
#   - Free indirect discourse: the narrator becomes the character's consciousness
#   - Distributed moral judgment: no one is entirely guilty or entirely innocent
#   - The web of interdependent lives: how one act ripples through a community
#   - The unlived life: what circumstances denied each character
#   - Moral humility: knowing the truth does not heal the wound
#
# Agatha Eliot hybrid:
#   - A murder is the disturbance that forces a community to confront its own
#     moral architecture — not a puzzle to be solved but a rupture to be
#     understood.
#   - The 'detective' is the community's conscience — not a brilliant outsider
#     but the slow, cumulative pressure of truth upon people who would prefer
#     not to see themselves clearly.
#   - The revelation emerges through multiple consciousnesses. No single
#     character holds the whole picture.
#   - The 'solution' is not a culprit's name but a reconfiguration of who
#     these people are to one another.
#
# =============================================================================
#}

{#
=============================================================================
CORE FORMS — The building blocks of Agatha Eliot's voice
=============================================================================
#}

{# ── The Forensic Declarative ────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Christie's atomic unit: state a fact clearly. No ornament. No evasion.
   The reader must be able to hold the fact in mind and weigh it against
   other facts. This is the detective's discipline.
#}

{% macro forensic_declarative(subject, predicate, object) %}
{{ subject | capitalize }} {{ predicate }} {{ object }}.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro the_facts_madame(fact) %}
The facts, as they presented themselves, were these: {{ fact }}.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── Free Indirect Interrogation ─────────────────────────────────────────────
   A Christie interrogation, but rendered through Eliot's free indirect
   discourse. We hear what the witness says AND what they cannot bring
   themselves to say. The gap is the clue.
#}

{% macro free_indirect_interrogation(witness, spoken, unspoken_thought) %}
"{{ spoken | trim }}," {{ witness }} said.
But what {{ witness }} did not say — what {{ witness }} could not bring
themselves to say, even to themselves — was that {{ unspoken_thought | trim }}.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro inner_interrogation(witness, question, inner_response) %}
{{ witness }} considered the question. {{ question | trim }}
And in the silence that followed, a thought stirred that had nothing
to do with the answer they would give aloud: {{ inner_response | trim }}
{% endmacro %}

{# ── The Widening Ripple ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Eliot's signature move: show how one act radiates outward through a
   web of interdependent lives. The murder is the stone; the novel is
   the widening circles.
#}

{% macro widening_ripple(event, first_affected, second_affected, third_affected) %}
{{ event | capitalize }}.
{{ first_affected | trim }}
{{ second_affected | trim }}
{{ third_affected | trim }}
And this was only the beginning — the first ring of a disturbance whose
full circumference no one present could yet measure.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── The Unlived Life ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Eliot's deepest insight: every character carries a parallel existence —
   what they might have been, what circumstances denied them. The crime
   reveals these absences.
#}

{% macro unlived_life(character, what_they_became, what_they_might_have_been) %}
{{ character }} had become {{ what_they_became }}.
But there was another {{ character }} who had never been permitted to exist —
the one who {{ what_they_might_have_been | trim }},
if the world had made room. The crime had room enough. The world did not.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── The Closed Circle as Crucible ───────────────────────────────────────────
   Christie's closed-circle suspects, reinterpreted through Eliot's moral
   lens. Every suspect's motive reveals a failure of the community, not
   merely a failure of character.
#}

{% macro closed_circle_crucible(suspects, shared_secret, community_failure) %}
Every one of them had a motive. Every one of them had kept {{ shared_secret }}.
And every one of them had believed they were alone in their deception —
which was the community's real failure: not that the secret existed, but
that {{ community_failure | trim }}.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── The Least Likely ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Christie's structural axiom, refracted through Eliot: the least likely
   person is frequently the guilty one — not because the world is perverse,
   but because we notice least what we take most for granted.
#}

{% macro least_likely(character, why_overlooked, what_they_carried) %}
No one suspected {{ character }}. {{ why_overlooked | trim }}
But {{ character }} had been carrying {{ what_they_carried | trim }}
for longer than anyone knew — and the weight of what is carried in
silence is heavier, in the end, than anything that is spoken aloud.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── The Revelation Through Consciousness ────────────────────────────────────
   The Christie revelation scene, reconstructed: no single character delivers
   the monologue. The truth emerges through multiple consciousnesses, each
   seeing only part of the picture.
#}

{% macro revelation_through_consciousness(character_a_insight, character_b_insight, character_c_insight) %}
The truth did not arrive all at once.
{{ character_a_insight | capitalize | trim }}
{{ character_b_insight | capitalize | trim }}
{{ character_c_insight | capitalize | trim }}
And in the space between these partial recognitions, the full shape of
what had happened became visible — not to any one of them, but to the
silence that now held them all.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── The Distributed Verdict ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Eliot's moral framework applied to Christie's resolution: justice is
   partial, guilt is distributed, some wounds do not close.
#}

{% macro distributed_verdict(guilty_party, unindicted_complicity, what_remains_broken) %}
{{ guilty_party }} was guilty. The facts permitted no other conclusion.
But what the facts could not capture was that {{ unindicted_complicity | trim }}.
{{ what_remains_broken | trim }}
The verdict was clear. The clarity was not the same thing as healing.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── Order and Method ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Christie's epistemological discipline: arrange the facts, find the pattern.
   Eliot adds: the pattern will reveal not only what happened but what
   everyone needed to believe about what happened.
#}

{% macro order_and_method(facts_arranged, pattern_revealed, belief_revealed) %}
{{ facts_arranged | trim }}. The pattern was {{ pattern_revealed | trim }}.
But the pattern also revealed something that no one had thought to look for:
{{ belief_revealed | trim }} — and the discovery of what everyone had needed
to believe was, in its way, more disturbing than the crime itself.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── The Stone and the Circles ───────────────────────────────────────────────
   The frame for an opening scene: the crime reported with Christie's
   forensic clarity, but rendered through the consciousness of whoever
   discovered the body.
#}

{% macro stone_and_circles(crime, discoverer, immediate_thought, deeper_thought) %}
{{ crime | capitalize }}.
{{ discoverer }} found the body. {{ immediate_thought | trim }}
And then, beneath that first thought — {{ deeper_thought | trim }}
{% endmacro %}

